, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2021/11/Structure-of-β-D-glucose.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Alpha glucose (top) has the hydrogen above carbon 1 and the OH group below, while beta glucose (bottom) has the hydrogen below carbon 1 and the OH group above</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="monosaccharides-function">Monosaccharides: Function</h2><ul><li><p>The main function of monosaccharides is <b>to store energy </b>within their bonds</p><ul><li><p>When the bonds are broken during <span class="popovers" data-content="The chemical process by which energy is released from glucose to produce ATP inside living cells. Aerobic respiration requires oxygen, while anaerobic respiration does not." data-title="Respiration" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">respiration</span>, energy is released</p></li></ul></li><li><p>The structure of glucose is related to its function as the main energy store for animals and plants </p><ul><li><p>It is <b>soluble</b> so can be transported easily</p></li><li><p>It has many <b>covalent bonds which store energy</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Monosaccharides can combine through <span class="popovers" data-content="An organic reaction in which two molecules join together to form one molecule and eliminate a small molecule such as water" data-title="Condensation reaction" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">condensation reactions</span> to form larger carbohydrates</p></li><li><p>Some monosaccharides are used to <b>form long, structural fibers,</b> which can be used as cellular support in some cell types</p></li></ul></div></div></div>